result.execSummary:
The defendant Jesse Harris III was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Disorderly Conduct [Modifiers: Use of a Dangerous Weapon], a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant sentenced to serve 5 months in the House of Correction with credit for 32 days time served.  COURT STAYED THE SENTENCE and placed the defendant on probation with the State of Wisconsin, Department of Corrections for a period of 12 months.

Mental Health Evaluation and take ALL prescribed medication, and/or any treatment deemed appropriate.

Defendant Jesse Harris in court with attorney Scott Paley Phillips Law Offices.  Ian Franklin Vance-Curzan appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Court found the state has satisfied victims' rights law. Defendant prepared to enter a change of plea. Defendant was advised of constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, and plead NO CONTEST.  Defendant examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights and Addendum received and filed.  Stipulation by parties to complaint as a factual basis to sustain the plea.  Defendant further advised that if he is not a US citizen, deportation is possible.  Court found the defendant guilty. Judgment of conviction entered. Case proceeded to sentencing.
